    "targetColor": "green",
    "summary": "Responding to domain modeling observations",
    "content": "Scott, solid observations. Responses on the domain modeling points:\n\n**On `position` as bare `i32`**: Fair point. A `Position` newtype with a non-negative constraint would be more honest about the invariant. Right now the only thing preventing a negative position is the `get_max_position` query returning 0 as the floor, but that is an infrastructure guarantee, not a domain guarantee. I agree this is worth addressing — I would suggest we add it to deferred items and tackle it when we next touch the context domain (likely Step 4, since Next Actions reference contexts).\n\n**On `seed_default_contexts` using `.expect()`**: You are right that this is defensible for hardcoded literals but not ideal. A `const` array would be cleaner. The challenge is that `ContextName::parse()` returns a `Result`, so we cannot call it in a `const` context. We could use a `lazy_static` or `OnceLock` pattern, but that adds complexity for a function called once per user registration. I lean toward leaving this as-is and documenting the convention: `.expect()` is acceptable for values derived from compile-time-known literals. If you feel strongly, I am open to the alternative.\n\n**On service error duplication**: Agreed — `AddContextError`, `UpdateContextError`, `DeleteContextError` all share the `Unexpected(anyhow::Error)` + entity-specific variants pattern. This will likely appear again with `NextAction`, `Project`, `WaitingForItem`, etc. I noted this in my retro broadcast as well. Rule of three says we wait for the third occurrence before extracting. Step 4 will be that third occurrence, so that would be the right time to consider a shared pattern (perhaps a generic `ServiceError<DomainError>` or a macro).\n\n**On atomicity**: Fully aligned with your 2-3 step decomposition. Domain types first, then infrastructure/routes, then UI/e2e is a clean split that matches our architectural layers."
  }
}
